        "Description of collaboration and any progress, if applicable": "With the funding support from the ECF, the ECC has rolled out the two-year Carbon Neutrality Publicity Campaign (CNPC) 1.0 to enhance public awareness on the imminence of the climate crisis, and instil a sense of urgency to start adopting a low-carbon lifestyle since late 2022. The CNPC adopts the overarching theme of carbon neutrality, with three sub-themes, viz. energy saving, green transport, and waste reduction and recycling. To sustain the momentum of the awareness built under the CNPC1.0, CNPC2.0 was launched from Q3 2024 to encourage the public to transform carbon reduction awareness into action, change their daily habits, practise low-carbon living together, aiming at achieving carbon reduction by 2050. Around 150 strategic and collaboration partners including public and business corporations, industry groups, non-governmental organisations and schools sponsoring bodies have been engaged to jointly promote low-carbon living to their stakeholders and/or publicize the campaign on their premises, social media and website.\\n\\n\\nTo strengthen the publicity and education on waste reduction and recycling in the community and at school level, the Environmental Protection Department (EPD) launched the “We-recycle@School” Activity on 1 March 2024, to encourage students to actively practise resource separation and recycling together with their family members to cultivate habits of waste reduction and recycling in their daily lives. As at June 2025, around 550 primary and secondary schools in Hong Kong have participated in the programme, covering about 350 000 students.\\nRegarding the Regulation on Disposable Plastic Tableware and Other Plastic Products (the Regulation), in order to reduce the use of disposable plastic tableware and other plastic products with a view to reducing the impact of plastic pollution on marine ecology and human health and mitigating climate change, the EPD and the former Council for Sustainable Development launched a public consultation on the Scheme on Regulation of Disposable Plastic Tableware (Regulation Scheme) in July 2021 and a public engagement on control of single-use plastics in September 2021, respectively. During these periods, more than 30 briefings, public forums, focus group meetings etc. were held to collect opinions on the proposed Regulation Scheme from the public, the trade and various stakeholders, including the catering industry, catering suppliers, green groups, medical sector, retail sector, wholesale sector, chambers of commerce, recycling sector and other professional bodies. Thereafter, we continued to keep close communication with the major stakeholders.\\n\\nTo assist the trade in understanding which alternatives comply with the Regulation with a view to facilitating the trade in the early adoption of more environmental-friendly non-plastic tableware (such as paper and plant fibre), in lieu of the disposable plastic ones, we established a “Green Tableware Platform” (www.greentableware.hk) in January 2022. To ensure that the products meet the plastic-free requirement of the Regulation, the platform secretariat reviews the tableware to be placed on the platform in each application, through assessing information such as material testing reports, certifications and product samples, etc.\\n",
