    "q2_1_1": [
      {
        "question_text": "Provide details on your climate risk and vulnerability assessment.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "Assessment direct link^": "Hong Kong Climate Change Report 2015 \\nCoastal hazard assessments under climate change and extreme weathers (details can be found in our input for 5.1.1 and 9.1.) (https://www.eeb.gov.hk/sites/default/files/pdf/ClimateChangeEng.pdf)\\n",
        "Confirm attachment/link provided to assessment": "The assessment can be accessed (unrestricted) on the link provided",
        "Boundary of assessment relative to jurisdiction boundary^": "Same - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "Year of publication or approval": 2015.0,
        "Factors considered in assessment": "Assessment considers nature|Assessment considers water security",
        "Please explain": "The assessment can be accessed (unrestricted) on the link provided (https://www.eeb.gov.hk/sites/default/files/pdf/ClimateChangeEng.pdf)\\n"
      },
      {
        "question_text": "Provide details on your climate risk and vulnerability assessment.",
        "row_order": 3,
        "row_name": "Row 3",
        "Assessment direct link^": "Study of Coastal Hazards under Climate Change and Extreme Weather and Formulation of Improvement Measures - Feasibility Study \\n(https://www.cedd.gov.hk/eng/media-corner/project-reports/index-id-24.html)\\n\\nStudy on Shoreline Management Plan\\n(https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr2025/english/panels/dev/papers/dev20250527cb1-904-4-e.pdf)\\n",
        "Confirm attachment/link provided to assessment": "The assessment can be accessed (unrestricted) on the link provided",
        "Boundary of assessment relative to jurisdiction boundary^": "Same - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "Year of publication or approval": 2015.0,
        "Factors considered in assessment": "Assessment includes a high-emissions scenario (i.e., RCP 8.5)|Assessment considers vulnerable populations|Identified hazards have been incorporated into the jurisdiction's overall risk management framework",
        "Please explain": "In our climate risk and vulnerability assessments, we placed particular emphasis on vulnerable populations by identifying and prioritizing low-lying and exposed residential areas where community safety is most at risk from coastal hazards. Following risk management approach, we first deal with those locations susceptible to higher risk with greater consequence. Most people will stay at home when typhoon strikes. To address the prime concern of human safety, coastal areas with residential developments vulnerable to potential coastal risks are identified, where priority should be accorded to formulate enhancement measures to alleviate the implications of extreme weather to the public and to enhance the resilience of the community.\\n\\nThe assessment analysed climate risks under both intermediate (SSP2-4.5) and very high (SSP5-8.5, equivalent to RCP 8.5) greenhouse gas emissions scenarios, ensuring our strategies remain robust under pessimistic climate conditions. Furthermore, the identified hazards have been integrated into the jurisdiction's overall risk management framework through a risk-based approach primarily considering the likelihood of coastal hazards and the severity of their potential consequences. It also considers a range of factors, such as existing topography, land use, flood risk, impacts on the surrounding environment, the defense capability of current facilities, as well as technical feasibility and cost-effectiveness of adaptation measures. This comprehensive process enables the development and prioritization of targeted adaptation, resilience, and management actions to safeguard public safety and enhance the community's resilience against future climate risks.\\n\\n\\nSupplement notes for 2.1.1.1\\nStudy of Coastal Hazards under Climate Change and Extreme Weather and Formulation of Improvement Measures - Feasibility Study \\nTo address increasing coastal flood risks due to sea level rise and storm surges, a Coastal Hazards Study (CHS) was completed in 2021. The study adopted a risk-based approach to identify and prioritize vulnerable areas, considering both the likelihood and severity of coastal hazards taking into account historical coastal flood events (e.g., super typhoons) and projected climate impacts. This study identified 26 low-lying or exposed coastal residential areas in Hong Kong as particularly vulnerable to coastal hazards. \\n\\nTo safeguard public safety and enhance community resilience, improvement works and management measures were formulated and have been progressively implemented since 2022 and for completion by 2027. \\n\\nStudy on Shoreline Management Plan \\nFurther to completion of CHS, we have recently completed the Shoreline Management Plan (SMP) Study at the end of 2024 to develop integrated and long-term strategy for managing shoreline risks under climate change. The SMP analysed the impacts of storm surges, waves, and sea level rise on coastal areas. The plan assessed risks under major climate change scenarios, including SSP2-4.5 (intermediate greenhouse gas emissions scenario) and SSP5-8.5 (very high greenhouse gas emissions scenario), for both mid-century (2050) and end-century (2100) time horizons. In addition to those 26 locations previously identified, with the risk-based approach, the study further identified 11 coastal areas planned for advance preparation to cope with the coastal risks near the mid-century.\\n\\nThe SMP is established as a \\'live document\\' that will be reviewed and updated on a regular cycle, such as when the IPCC's AR7 released in future, ensuring alignment with the latest science and international best practices. This process ensures that the risk assessment is up to date.\\n\\nRisk Management Process for the studies\\nBoth studies adopted a risk management approach to identify coastal areas most susceptible to higher risks, primarily considering the likelihood of coastal hazards and the severity of their potential consequences. During the analysis, the studies referenced historical records of damage caused by coastal flooding during past super typhoon events to ensure a robust and evidence-based assessment.\\n"
      }
    ],
