        "Progress made towards target": "Hong Kong's fresh water and salt water supplies are provided through a network of over 8 400 kilometres of water mains. After the substantial completion of the 15-year replacement and rehabilitation programme for 3,000-kilometres aged water mains in 2015, the healthiness of the water supply networks has been greatly improved. Owing to the hilly terrain of Hong Kong, in order to maintain adequate water supply pressure for premises located at high ground, the water pressure of the water supply networks in Hong Kong generally ranges from 60 metres to 80 metres, which is higher than that of other cities. In addition, the water supply networks in Hong Kong are mostly underground. The congested underground public utilities, busy traffic and frequent repairs of the public utilities and roadworks, etc. all cause vibration and disturbance to the underground water mains. Therefore, the timescale for the risk will be “Medium term”.\\n\\nThe above factors cause an increase in the risk of water mains bursts and leakage in the water supply networks in Hong Kong, which have caused inconvenience to the public and resulted in water loss.\\n\\nRisk-based Water Main Asset Management\\nFollowing the substantial completion of the 15-year replacement and rehabilitation programme in 2015, the condition of the water distribution network has been largely improved with substantial reduction in number of main bursts from about 2 500 cases in 2000 by 98% to about 37 cases in 2024, and leakage rate from exceeding 25% in 2000 to about 13.4% in 2023. In order to maintain the healthiness of the water supply network, a risk-based water main asset management strategy is being implemented to maintain the healthiness of the water supply networks and reduce the risk of water main bursts or leaks. It is a proactive management strategy aimed to prevent as far as practicable the failure of the water mains by rendering priorities to those water mains with high risk for improvement works including replacement or rehabilitation. The risk is assessed taking into account various factors including the consequences of bursts or leaks, ages and materials of the water mains, past records of bursts or leaks, surrounding environment, etc. Besides, improvement works to water mains in “main burst hot spots” (i.e. locations with repeated water main bursts) are also carried out.\\n\\nWater Intelligent Network (WIN)\\nSince 2016, the Water Supplies Department (WSD) has been establishing the Water Intelligence Network (WI"
