    "q8_4": [
      {
        "question_text": "Does your jurisdiction have a strategy or standard for reducing emissions from the jurisdiction's procurement and purchase of goods and services?",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "Response": "Yes",
        "Provide a link, if applicable, and highlight any specific action(s) the jurisdiction is implementing to reduce emissions from its own consumption": "Links: \\nGreen Procurement Information Portal -\\nhttps://www.eeb.gov.hk/en/susdev/green_procure/green_procure.html\\n\\nGovernment Circular on “Green Procurement in the Government” -\\nhttps://www.eeb.gov.hk/en/susdev/green_procure/scr/ENB_CM_1-2021.pdf\\n\\nElectronic systems:\\n\\nhttps://www1.ets.gov.hk/eTp_ext/views/index.zul\\nhttps://pcms2.gld.gov.hk/iprod/#/home\\nhttps://www.gov.hk/tc/theme/eprocurement/eppp/\\n\\n\\nSpecific actions:\\n1. The Government has all along led by example by adopting green procurement for implementation of the concept of environmental protection. The Government's Stores and Procurement Regulations require bureaux and departments (B/Ds) to take environmental factors into consideration in drawing up tender specifications, so as to allow for fair competition of compliant products and services on a cost-effective basis, thereby promoting green procurement while ensuring the prudent use of public funds. \\n\\nHaving regard to the practices and standards generally adopted in the market, the Government has developed a set of green specifications and guidelines for the products and services commonly used by the Government, so that B/Ds may practise green procurement in accordance with the relevant specifications. The Government reviews the green procurement list and relevant specifications from time to time to keep abreast of the latest market development and the procurement needs of B/Ds. In July 2021, the Government expanded the green procurement list from 150 to 183 items, updating the specifications for each product and providing additional tips for green procurement. In February 2024, the Government updated the green procurement circular to set electric vehicles as the standard for the procurement or replacement of all government private cars as far as possible. Recently, the Government further updated the green specifications for the procurement of LED lamps with motion sensor function and filtered water dispensers. In 2024, the Government procured green products and services with a total value of $8.42 billion, which is an increase of about 19.3% as compared to $7.06 billion in 2023. The Government will continue to promote green procurement by disseminating the latest green procurement list, relevant specifications, tips and both local and international best practices online for public reference.\\n\\n\\n2. The Environmental Protection Department is using the electronic procurement system to handle the quotation exercises. The Environmental Protection Department also adopts the electronic tendering system for processing tendering matters and receiving electronic submission of offer. The subject teams of the Environmental Protection Department are required to adopt the green procurement practice with details as stipulated in the Environment Bureau Circular Memorandum No. 1/2021."
      }
    ],
