        "Select a reference ID for the action": "Adaptation Action 4",
        "Action^": "Engineered and built environment actions: Other: (cont) Collaboration &Enhancing Public Awareness",
        "Climate hazard(s) that action addresses": "Coastal flooding (incl. sea level rise)|Extreme wind|Other coastal events|Hurricanes, cyclones, and/or typhoons",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "(Cont)\\n\\nManagement Measures - Action Plan\\n\\n We adopt a practical and prioritized approach to reducing coastal risks, recognizing that not all coastal areas can be fully protected through infrastructure enhancements alone due to factors such as site constraints, cost-effectiveness, and potential impacts on marine traffic, social activities, and the environment. Therefore, it is equally important to implement appropriate management measures, such as early warning systems and emergency response plans, to enhance community preparedness, response, and resilience in addressing residual risks that may remain after physical defenses (“hardware”) are in place. In addition to ongoing infrastructure improvements, we have established a range of management (“software”) measures, including the execution of emergency response action plans during typhoon season. Sandbags are made available in various locations for public use during emergencies. When a typhoon approaches Hong Kong, duty teams inspect sandbag storage in remote and island areas and arrange for contractors to replenish supplies as needed. As the typhoon intensifies, sandbags are also distributed to locations accessible by land, with contractors assisting in transportation and distribution. The latest information is disseminated to the public through social media platforms to keep everyone informed. Routine inspections and maintenance of marine facilities are conducted, and after a Typhoon Signal No. 8 or above, immediate post-storm inspections are carried out to ensure the structural safety and proper functioning of ferry piers and essential marine infrastructure.\\n\\nPublic Education\\nAdditionally, public education plays a vital role in enhancing Hong Kong's capability to cope with extreme weather. We actively engage relevant stakeholders and the general public through TV announcements, publications, international conferences, government open days, seminars for government departments and stakeholders (including utility providers and professional bodies), and various outreach education programs. These efforts aim to raise awareness of climate risks, promote understanding of improvement measures and emergency preparedness, and ultimately strengthen the community's resilience to extreme weather and climate change.\\n",
