        "row_name": "Row 9",
        "Select a reference ID for the action": "Mitigation Action 9",
        "Primary emissions sector addressed and action type^": "Transportation: Other: Green Public Transport, Procurement of zero emissions buses, Electric vehicle charging points and infrastructure, Procurement of electric vehicles for government fleet",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "- Promotion of the use of EVs in public transport & Procurement of zero emissions public transport: \\n\\n- First registration tax (FRT) concession arrangement for electric vehicles (including electric public transport vehicles) has been in place since 1994 and will continue until 31 March 2026. More details can be found at https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/202402/28/P2024022800393.htm?fontSize=1. \\n\\nProcurement of zero emission public transport\\n\\n- The Government has put in place a HK$1,100 million (about US$140 million) New Energy Transport Fund (previously named Pilot Green Transport Fund) since March 2011 to subsidise the transport sector and non-profit making organisations to try out and more widely use of green innovative and low carbon transport technologies. More details can be found at https://www.eeb.gov.hk/en/new-energy-transport-fund/new-energy-transport-fund.html. \\n\\n- The Government earmarked $135 million (about US$17 million) and about $470 million (about US$60 million) respectively under the New Energy Transport Fund to subsidise the purchase of 3 000 e-taxis by the taxi trade and about 600 e-buses by the franchised bus operators. More details can be found at https://www.eeb.gov.hk/en/new-energy-transport-fund/AU.html. The Government also earmarked $50 million (about US$6.4 million) under the New Energy Transport Fund to subsidise the taxi trade to procure wheelchair accessible e-taxis. More details can be found at: https://www.eeb.gov.hk/en/new-energy-transport-fund/AU.html#e-Taxi%20Subsidy%20Scheme \\n\\nTrial and pilot schemes for zero emission public transport \\n\\n- The Government allocated HKD180 million (about USD 23 million) for franchised bus companies to purchase 36 single-deck electric buses and their charging facilities for trial since 2015.\\n\\n- The Government allocated HKD 80 million (about USD 10 million) for trial of electric public light buses and the associated charging facilities. The first and second rounds of operational trials have commenced since March 2024 and February 2025 respectively. \\n\\nThe Government allocated HKD 350 million (about 18USD 45 million) to implement the Pilot Scheme of Electric Ferries in four in-habour ferry routes to test out the operation of electric ferries.\\n\\nEV charging points and infrastructure for zero emission public transport vehicles:\\n\\n- The Government allocated HKD 10.8 million (about USD 1.38 million) to provide 12 dedicated fast charging facilities for electric taxi. All these fast charging facilities have already been put into services in phases from Q4-2023 to Q2-2025. \\n\\n- The Government is gradually transforming some existing petrol filling stations into fast charging stations (FCSs) or petrol filling cum charging stations for diversifying charging facilities to meet the charging need of various types of EVs (including electric public transport vehicles). In addition, the Government is providing incentives to existing PFS operators, including modifying land lease to encourage them to retrofit EV charging facilities at usable space of existing PFSs so as to make the effective use of about 180 PFSs throughout the territory to provide charging services for EVs. More details can be found at https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr2024/english/panels/ea/papers/ea20240422cb1-442-3-e.pdf. \\n",
