        "Provide a link, if applicable, and highlight any specific action the jurisdiction is implementing to reduce emissions from the consumption of goods and services in this category": "https://www.tbkc.gov.tw/Policy/PolicyPush/Sustainable Kaohsiung City has been promoting the adoption of green public transport. By October 2022, the government had already replaced 203,900 scooters with two-stroke engines, surpassing every other region in Taiwan. In addition, the government also built bicycle tracks alongside MRT stations, spanning 1,047.9 kilometers.The City's bike-sharing system also underwent a major update. In July 2020, the old C-bike system was replaced by the upgraded version, YouBike 2.0, with service run by the eponymous company YouBike. In December of the same year alone, the service had been used over one million times. In March 2021, the service also saw its highest daily usage number of 48,000. By August of the same year, the service had been used over 10 million times. By November 2023, the City had reached its target of setting up 1,274 bike-sharing stations.\\nBy April 2023, the government had introduced 295 electric busses to the City, which accounted for 20% of vehicles in its bus fleet. The government aims to push the percentage to 60% by 2025 and offer fully electric city buses service by 2030.\\nTo encourage the use of public transportation, Kaohsiung City is optimizing its Mobility-as-a-Service (MaaS) system by integrating various public transit services. Through the promotion of the TPASS monthly commuter pass and continuous outreach via multiple channels, the city aims to enhance public awareness and foster stronger support for public transportation."
