        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Regarding the phenomena and trends of climate change, the IPCC Sixth Assessment Report (AR6) estimates that global surface warming caused by human activities from 1850-1900 to 2010-2019 is approximately 1.07°C (with a range of 0.8°C-1.3°C). Greenhouse gases alone are responsible for approximately 1.0°C-2.0°C of warming, while other human-induced factors, such as aerosols, have contributed to a cooling effect of 0-0.8°C. Natural drivers have influenced surface temperature changes only within the range of -0.1°C to +0.1°C.\\n\\nClimate change—particularly extreme heat—has contributed to the emergence of new types of diseases, which may manifest in various forms and may exceed the response capacity of medical institutions in some regions.\\n\\nIn New Taipei City, the proportion of elderly residents continues to increase. Without improved adaptive capacity, areas with a high concentration of elderly populations and insufficient medical infrastructure may be particularly vulnerable.\\n\\nAccording to the High-Temperature Intensity Hazard Map provided by the Taiwan Climate Change Projection and Adaptation Knowledge Platform (TCCIP), eight administrative districts in New Taipei City have the highest potential for extreme heat intensity: Luzhou, Sanchong, Xinzhuang, Banqiao, Zhonghe, Yonghe, Shulin, and Yingge Districts. These eight districts collectively account for approximately 60-70% of the city's total population.",
