        "Climate-related hazards^": "Drought",
        "Vulnerable population groups most exposed": "Indigenous peoples|Low-income households|Frontline workers|Children and youth|Elderly|Outdoor workers|Marginalized/minority communities|Women and girls|Vulnerable health groups",
        "Sectors most exposed^": "Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Forestry|Human health and social work activities|Agriculture|Water supply",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "During drought events that lead to water shortages or supply disruptions, the most immediately affected are those who depend on stable water resources for their livelihoods, such as farmers in the rain-fed agricultural zones of New Taipei City's mountainous areas and aquaculture operators along the coast. These sectors face risks such as crop failure and reduced fish harvests, resulting in significant economic losses. Meanwhile, declining water levels may impact hydropower generation and cooling systems, potentially causing regional power outages or electricity rationing, further disrupting industrial and commercial operations as well as the stable functioning of medical facilities.\\n\\nResidents living in low-lying, remote, or non-piped areas without access to the public water supply system are also at greater risk during droughts. This is especially true for elderly individuals, people with chronic illnesses, and economically disadvantaged households, who often lack alternative water sources or cooling equipment, making them more vulnerable to water scarcity, deteriorating sanitary conditions, and heat-related illnesses such as heatstroke.\\n\\nUrban areas with aging settlements or clusters of illegal housing structures are also highly susceptible during drought periods due to the lack of drought-resilient infrastructure and limited capacity for water storage.\\n\\nDroughts further exacerbate water quality degradation and increase sanitation-related risks. Areas without access to clean drinking water and adequate wastewater treatment systems are more likely to experience outbreaks of waterborne diseases or food safety issues, posing long-term public health threats. Additionally, the alternating occurrence of droughts and floods can lead to imbalances in water resource allocation, placing even greater pressure on vulnerable populations.",
