        "Sectors most exposed^": "Transportation and storage",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "According to statistics from the Agency of Rural Development and Soil and Water Conservation, New Taipei City's total land area is 205,257 hectares, with 110,076 hectares classified as slopeland, accounting for 54% of the city's total area. Except for the four areas of Banqiao, Sanchong, Luzhou, and Yonghe, which are alluvial plains, the remaining 25 districts include slopeland areas.\\n\\nIn recent years, rapid industrial and commercial development has led to a swift expansion of non-agricultural land uses, such as construction, industrial zones, roads, and mining. This, combined with the expansion of the Greater Taipei Metropolitan Area, has led to the saturation of flat land resources in New Taipei City. Consequently, large-scale slopeland community development projects have emerged.\\n\\nHowever, since the 921 Earthquake, surface cracks and loosened joints in slopeland rock slopes, along with the effects of climate change and extreme rainfall events, have increased the frequency of landslides and debris flows, heightening disaster risks for slopeland communities located in landslide-prone areas and near slopes, fault lines, and debris flow potential zones.\\n\\nAccording to the Agency of Rural Development and Soil and Water Conservation, New Taipei City has a total of 235 potential debris flow streams, with 27 located in Xindian District, the highest number in the city, followed by Sanxia District and Ruifang District.",
