        "Sectors most exposed^": "Human health and social work activities",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Taiwan is located in a subtropical region with abundant rainfall, which provides favorable conditions for the breeding of dengue fever vector mosquitoes.\\n\\nAs climate change causes warmer winters and rising annual temperatures, the survival rate of Aedes aegypti mosquitoes during colder seasons has increased, along with an extended reproductive cycle and enhanced overwintering capacity. Additionally, more frequent extreme rainfall events create standing water, increasing breeding grounds and raising the risk of dengue fever transmission.\\n\\nIn 2018, New Taipei City reported 44 cases of dengue fever, most of which were linked to activities in community gardens. To control the outbreak, the city government restricted access to six high-risk community gardens.\\n\\nStarting in 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic and border controls, overseas travel was significantly reduced. After borders reopened in early 2023, international travel resumed. Meanwhile, the clinical symptoms of dengue fever are often difficult to distinguish from those of COVID-19, posing a severe public health challenge.\\n\\nAccording to statistics from the Centers for Disease Control under the Ministry of Health and Welfare, there were 113 confirmed cases of dengue fever in New Taipei City in 2024.",
