        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Due to climate change and intensified environmental disasters, the relationship between humans and ecology has become increasingly intertwined. In response, countries around the world have signed the Convention on Biological Diversity to achieve goals such as conserving biological and ecological diversity and ensuring the sustainable use of natural resources. To preserve the ecology of New Taipei City and promote an environmentally friendly agricultural system, the Agriculture Bureau is implementing various initiatives, including stream closures for fish conservation, restoration of native flora and fauna, management of nature reserves, reforestation, and the removal of invasive species. These efforts aim to maintain biodiversity and ensure the sustainable use of biological resources. Additionally, a variety of ecological activities, lectures, and volunteer training programs are being conducted to promote ecological conservation and raise public awareness of the city's valuable ecosystems.\\n\\nNative Plant Restoration in New Taipei City:\\n\\n(1)Wulai Azalea:\\nNative to the Beishi River area, the Wulai Azalea (Rhododendron nakaharai) has seen its natural habitat largely submerged due to the construction of the Shimen Reservoir, leading to its classification as Extinct in the Wild in the Red List of Taiwan Vascular Plants. In response, the Agriculture Bureau has launched restoration efforts, including cutting propagation in nurseries and collaboration with Professor Lin Jui-Chin of National Chiayi University, successfully cultivating 1,500 seedlings to enhance species diversity. Restoration outcomes can be observ.\\n\\n(2)Taiwan Lily:\\nThe Taiwan Lily (Lilium formosanum), an endemic species once widely distributed across the island, has seen a sharp decline in wild populations due to human harvesting and habitat destruction. To address this, the Agriculture Bureau has promoted restoration by collaborating with local communities to cultivate seedlings and plant them extensively in the wild. Restoration sites include cliff.\\n\\n(3)Scarlet Lily:\\nThe Scarlet Lily (Lilium speciosum var. gloriosoides), another native and endemic species, is facing serious survival challenges due to habitat destruction and overharvesting. It has been listed as Nationally Critically Endangered (NCR) in the Red List of Taiwan Vascular Plants. In response, the Agriculture Bureau has partnered with local communities to carry out promotion activities, seedling propagation, and in-situ planting. Cur.\\n\\n",
