        "Identify which vulnerable populations are affected by the selected health issue(s)": "Women and girls|Indigenous peoples|Frontline workers|Vulnerable health groups|Elderly|Other: Entire population|Children and youth|Low-income households",
        "What factors affect your jurisdiction's ability to address the selected health issues": "Lack of financial capacity and expertise/technical capacity|Other: Lack of manpower (diverted to emergency response).",
        "Comment": "With the intensification of climate change, the frequency and intensity of heavy rainfall events have increased. In urban areas, due to low-lying terrain and high levels of urban development, heavy rainfall leads to increased surface runoff, overwhelming drainage systems and resulting in flooding events of varying scales. According to the flood potential simulation results in the “New Taipei City Climate Action Achievement Report,” it is estimated that the number of people affected citywide by flooding of over 0.3 meters is 258,333 (6.57%), and by flooding of over 0.5 meters is 82,878 (2.10%). Urban flooding not only causes property damage but also carries health risks such as waterborne diseases and the aggravation of chronic illnesses. These impacts are particularly severe for groups such as children, the elderly, indigenous peoples, persons with mobility impairments, and low-income households, who have more difficulty accessing resources. Frontline personnel may also face risks of infection and overwork as a result. Communities generally face limitations in funding, knowledge, and technology, making it difficult to effectively respond to these health threats."
