        "What factors affect your jurisdiction's ability to address the selected health issues": "Lack of financial capacity",
        "Comment": "Under climate change, both the frequency and intensity of droughts have increased, posing a potential risk to the stability of water supply for New Taipei City's medical system. Medical institutions rely heavily on a stable and safe supply of tap water to maintain normal operations for surgeries, sterilization, dialysis, ward cleaning, and basic hygiene services. If the water supply is interrupted or water pressure is insufficient, the quality of medical services and patient safety will be directly affected. In particular, long-term care facilities and primary clinics in remote areas or those not connected to a direct water supply system are more likely to face problems of insufficient water storage and a lack of emergency resources during drought periods. As temperatures rise and the frequency of extreme heat increases, the demand for medical water supply also rises accordingly. In addition, if wastewater treatment or sanitation is affected during droughts and water restrictions, the risk of cross-infection and other medical hazards may also increase."
