    "q4_11": [
      {
        "question_text": "What percentage of your population is food insecure and/or lives in a food desert?",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "Data availability": "Data available for the percentage of population that lives in a food desert|Data available for the percentage of population that is food insecure",
        "Percentage of population that is food insecure": 0.89,
        "Percentage of population that lives in a food desert": 3.75,
        "Comment": "1. Percentage of population facing food insecurity\\nThe main causes of hunger in Taiwan are poverty, low income, and the limited mobility of elderly individuals living alone. Low-income households typically have low and unstable income, making it difficult to afford enough food. Elderly individuals living alone face hunger due to various reasons, including poor financial condition, lack of family support, lost contact with relatives, remote locations with limited access to food, or physical immobility and poor health that prevent them from preparing meals on their own. In the first quarter of 2025, there were approximately 36,336 individuals in the jurisdiction identified as low-income households or elderly individuals living alone, accounting for 0.89% of the total population. Considering the possible overlap with low-income households, persons with disabilities and homeless individuals were not included in the calculation.\\n*Elderly individuals living alone: Registered or actual residents of the city, aged 65 or above, living alone, and listed by the city government as care recipients after assessment.\\n*Low-income households: Registered or actual residents of the city, with an average monthly household income per person not exceeding NT$16,000, and total family-owned real estate not exceeding NT$4.2 million.\\n\\n2. Percentage of population living in a food desert\\nThe city is densely populated with hypermarkets, supermarkets, convenience stores, traditional markets, and night markets. According to real estate surveys, the four administrative districts with the highest supermarket density in Taiwan are all located in New Taipei City, namely Yonghe, Luzhou, Sanchong, and Banqiao. Yonghe District alone, with an area of just 5.71 square kilometers, has 30 supermarkets—equivalent to more than five supermarkets per square kilometer. The data reported in this questionnaire are based on the selection of 11 administrative districts—out of the city's total of 29 districts—that are located in mountainous or coastal areas and have relatively low population density, and the population of these districts was used for calculation."
      }
    ],
