        "Year data applies to": 2023.0,
        "Comment": "The total weight of food purchases in this study is 27,388 metric tons, which includes purchases for schools and hospitals.\\n\\n1.Schools:\\nThere are approximately 360,000 students enrolled in elementary, junior high, and senior high schools within the jurisdiction. The average number of students served daily is about 277,000, with 190 serving days throughout the year.\\nThe total amount of food purchased for school meals is 27,323 metric tons.\\n\\n2.Hospitals:\\nIn 2024, the total amount of food purchased for patients and staff meals in hospitals within the jurisdiction is 64.7 metric tons.\\n\\n3.Shelter dry food purchases:\\nThe city has implemented the “New Taipei City Disaster Relief and Livelihood Supplies Supply and Transportation Plan.” Under this plan, each district office makes food purchases independently, based on a three-level reserve strategy tailored to the traffic characteristics of high-risk areas. Quantities are calculated based on required safety stock levels, and procurement and expense verification are carried out by the respective district offices. As a result, there is no centralized statistical data available for shelter-related food purchases due to the variation in food types and quantities across districts."
