        "Action^": "Engineered and built environment actions: Storm and wastewater management",
        "Climate hazard(s) that action addresses": "Extreme heat|Urban flooding|Water stress|Drought",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "In recent years, with the rapid development of urban economies and the continuous construction of human-made facilities, the high proportion of impervious surfaces caused by intensive development has had multiple impacts on the urban environment. After rainfall, this leads to increased surface runoff and peak flow, directly affecting runoff patterns, resulting in urban flooding and changes in the urban microclimate.\\n\\nTo address the environmental changes and potential impacts caused by concentrated urban development, the New Taipei City Government has incorporated the concept of Low Impact Development (LID) into its urban water environment management strategies. By applying the principles of water retention, permeability, and reuse, the city aims to build a permeable (sponge) city. Through rainwater harvesting and infiltration facilities, runoff is reduced at the source, flood prevention capacity is enhanced, and the burden on drainage systems is alleviated. This approach mitigates the environmental impact of development and restores the urban hydrological cycle in line with the sponge city concept.\\n\\nIn 2016, New Taipei City enacted the nation's first Water Retention and Permeability Autonomy Regulations, followed by the Technical Regulations on Water Retention and Permeability in New Taipei City in 2017. These regulations prioritize self-retention of rainwater and stipulate that all types of development sites and new constructions—including parks, roads, schools, and private buildings—are responsible for rainwater retention.\\n\\nGoing forward, the city will continue to promote water retention and permeability by repurposing existing public facilities into such systems, transforming New Taipei into a truly breathable sponge city and a low-carbon city.\\n\\nSpecific Measures and Details: \\n1.Revise the Water Retention and Permeability Autonomy Regulations and the Outflow Control Review Guidelines of New Taipei City.\\n2.Conduct inspections on completed water retention and permeability facilities to ensure they are functioning properly.\\n3.By 2028, the cumulative volume of water retention facilities will reach 2.68 million tons, and outflow control facilities will reach 500,000 tons.\\n\\nAs of 2023, sponge city construction projects have achieved a total water infiltration and retention capacity of 2.55 million metric tons, roughly equivalent to 1,020 standard swimming pools.\\n\\nLinks: \\n1.A Sponge City Must Not Be Breached: Everyone Has a Responsibility to Maintain Water Retention and Permeability Facilities in New Taipei https://reurl.cc/ekDy0x\\n\\n2.Water Retention and Permeability Zone, New Taipei City Water Resources Department\\nhttps://www.wrs.ntpc.gov.tw/home.jsp?id=626b55e7122050f7\\n\\n3.Implementation Results of Urban Water Retention and Permeability Measures\\nhttps://reurl.cc/OmRr67\\n\\n",
