        "Action^": "Services actions: Other: Care Mechanisms for the Homeless and Elderly Living Alone",
        "Climate hazard(s) that action addresses": "Extreme cold|Extreme heat",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "The “New Taipei City Government's High Temperature Response Action Plan” and the “New Taipei City Government's Cold Wave Preparedness Action Plan” have been formulated and implemented to ensure that homeless individuals and elderly people living alone are properly cared for during periods of extreme heat and cold, thereby reducing harm to these two vulnerable groups. \\n\\n1.To prevent respiratory or cardiovascular diseases that may be triggered by low temperatures, the city launches cold weather alerts when temperatures drop to 12°C or below. When temperatures fall to 10°C, district offices are notified to initiate the cold weather care mechanism:\\n(1)District offices and public area management units are instructed to dispatch personnel and coordinate with neighborhood chiefs, community resources, volunteers, social workers, or police to strengthen outreach and care services for the homeless. Depending on need, they may provide sleeping bags and warm clothing, establish hot meal service stations, and open temporary cold shelters.\\n(2)Community resources and volunteers are mobilized to enhance care and check-ins for elderly individuals living alone, and to provide information on staying warm and preventing cold-related harm.\\n\\n2.To mitigate heat-related illnesses, the \\'High Temperature Response Action Plan\\' is activated when temperatures exceed 36°C for three consecutive days, or 38°C on a single day. The following measures are taken:\\n(1)Conduct check-ins with elderly individuals living alone and provide information on heat protection.\\n(2)Display messages on preventing heat-related illnesses via electronic signage or posters in government office buildings.\\n(3)Coordinate with district offices to distribute drinking water and provide heat protection information on the streets. Fire stations, police stations, and other facilities are opened as cooling centers to safeguard the homeless.\\n(4)Collaborate with community resources, neighborhood chiefs, or volunteers to enhance heat awareness campaigns at major gathering points for homeless individuals, provide information on cooling shelters, and, when necessary, coordinate with district offices to supply drinking water and other necessities.\\n\\nLinks: \\n1.New Taipei City's Six Major Care Service Networks for the Homeless https://wedid.ntpc.gov.tw/Governance/Detail/oxXQLzn3LR19 \\n\\n2.Cold Surge Alert: New Taipei City Cares for the Homeless and Elderly Living Alone with Night Visits and Distribution of Winter Supplies\\nhttps://www.ntpc.gov.tw/ch/home.jsp?id=28&dataserno=202412130055\\n\\n3.Heat Wave Alert: New Taipei City Initiates Cooling and Care Mechanism for the Homeless and Elderly Living Alone; Reminds Facilities to Avoid Displacing the Homeless but Maintain Cleanliness \\nhttps://reurl.cc/1Ok1NQ\\n\\n4.Implementation Results of Preparedness Measures for Heatwaves and Cold Surges\\nhttps://reurl.cc/1OkbkX ",
