        "Primary emissions sector addressed and action type^": "Stationary energy: Requirements which incentivize net zero carbon, Passivhaus or other ultra-high-efficiency standards for new buildings",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": " To reduce dependence on the power grid, future buildings should be equipped with energy generation and storage systems. In addition to introducing zero-carbon design in large-scale development projects, new buildings will be required to install renewable energy and storage facilities starting in 2030. Through the establishment of net-zero energy consumption standards and regulations on resource and energy use, buildings can be planned holistically from design and construction to operation, including energy management systems, solar photovoltaic and storage facilities, and water recycling systems. By 2045, new buildings are expected to meet the 1+ level energy efficiency standard, focusing on the three core zero-carbon concepts of energy conservation, energy storage, and energy generation.\\n\\nIn addition, the New Taipei City Government has designated the Xintai Wenzaizun Urban Land Consolidation Area as its first demonstration zone. In this area, construction projects along the 30-meter main roads must be set back at least 10 meters, with the additional space designated for pedestrian walkways. There are strict requirements for the selection of street tree species, planting density, and the location of building entrances and exits, all aimed at creating the New Taipei Green Avenue. Vehicle entrances and exits on both sides of the buildings must avoid disrupting pedestrian access; if the number of access points cannot be reduced, their orientation must be adjusted. In addition, building facades facing the road must avoid exposing external air conditioning units.\\n\\nAlong both sides of Guizikeng Creek, the development concept emphasizes an eco-friendly environment that extends water flow and promotes rainwater infiltration for groundwater recharge. Shaded green walking paths will be created, and buildings facing the waterfront will be subject to facade width restrictions to mitigate the urban heat island effect. Through this development, New Taipei City aims to transform its urban landscape, address climate challenges, and move toward a sustainable, zero-carbon future. The Xintai Wenzaizun area will serve as a model for future comprehensive development projects.\\n\\nLinks: \\n1.Website of the Economic Development Department's “New Taipei City Green Roof Public Participation Program”\\nhttps://www.edbeis.ntpc.gov.tw/meeting.php?types=green \\n\\n2.New Taipei City 2050 Net Zero Roadmap and Climate Action White Paper https://www.epd.ntpc.gov.tw/Article/Info?ID=9620",
