        "Primary emissions sector addressed and action type^": "Other, please specify: Other: Protecting Marine Resources and Promoting Sustainable Fisheries",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "1. The New Taipei City Government plans to replace traditional fuels used in large agricultural machinery and diesel used in fishing vessels with hydrogen energy and biofuels.\\n\\n2. Mountain and Ocean Afforestation Project: Since the launch ceremony of the “New Taipei Mountain and Coastal Afforestation Project - Marine Afforestation and Coral Restoration” on June 25, 2022, the city has planted 500 coral colonies annually in its territorial waters to continuously safeguard the marine environment through concrete actions.\\n\\n3.Sustainable Marine Resources\\n(1) Regulated Fishery Management: New Taipei City continues to regulate and assist the transformation of gillnet fishing boats into other types of fishing using alternative gear. Fishery patrols are carried out within 3 nautical miles along the city's northern and northeastern coasts. From 2019 to 2024, a total of 584 patrol missions were conducted, effectively deterring violations.\\n\\n(2) Removal of Ghost Nets in Coastal Waters:\\nFrom 2012 to 2024, a total of 36,113.8 kilograms of ghost nets were removed from protected reef zones within the city's waters.\\n\\n(3) Planning of Aquatic Conservation and No-Fishing Zones: In 2012, the city completed seabed surveys and defined boundaries for the Gongliao Conservation Area and Aodi Artificial Reef No-Fishing Zone, and subsequently revised the boundaries of its fishery resource conservation areas based on updated seabed conditions to improve restoration effectiveness. In 2013, the Shenao Artificial Reef No-Fishing Zone was revised, and the Guihou and Yehliu artificial reef zones were consolidated into the Wanli Artificial Reef No-Fishing Zone. In 2014, comprehensive planning was carried out for artificial reef and no-fishing zones in Tamsui, Linkou, Bali, and Tiaoshi, as well as the northern coral reef areas. Adjustments were made to the reef point locations in Tamsui and Tiaoshi. In 2015, an ecological survey was conducted in Mao'ao Bay, and underwater live-stream monitoring points were established. In 2016, additional underwater surveillance cameras were installed at designated sites. In 2017, a survey on the status of ghost nets in Wanli's coastal waters was conducted. In 2019, the Yehliu Aquatic Plant and Animal Breeding Conservation Area was officially designated and announced.\\n\\n(4) Species Cultivation and Marine Education:\\nSince 2019, the city has continued to enhance mass production techniques for species such as cuttlefish and swimming crabs. In 2021, an intermediate breeding base was established at Meiyanshan Fishing Port, and in both 2022 and 2023, eight species were bred and released into the wild. Additionally, since 2019, the city has promoted the “New Taipei Marine Conservation Education Program”, including the Coral Classroom, which has attracted over 6,000 participants. As of 2024, 2,690 coral colonies have been cultivated. In July 2024, the Coral Classroom was held at the Marine Resource Restoration Park, where 465 coral colonies were planted in the coral cultivation ponds to raise public awareness and participation in marine restoration efforts.\\n\\nLink: \\n1.New Taipei City 2050 Net Zero Roadmap and Climate Action White Paper https://www.epd.ntpc.gov.tw/Article/Info?ID=9620\\n\\n2.Protecting Marine Resources and Promoting Sustainable Fisheries\\nhttps://wedid.ntpc.gov.tw/Governance/Detail/onWBPwbXv7q4\\n",
