        "Identified financing model": "Other: Private Finance Initiative (PFI)",
        "Project description and URL link, if applicable": "In 2015, New Taipei City adopted the Private Finance Initiative (PFI) model to replace 240,000 streetlights with energy-efficient LED lamps. The total project cost was NT$2.181 billion. By introducing private-sector financing, the City was able to avoid substantial upfront capital expenditures, reduce long-term electricity costs, and optimize the procurement and maintenance efficiency of street lighting equipment.\\n\\nEnvironmental benefits have also been significant. The project reduces approximately 99,000 metric tons of carbon dioxide emissions per year, equivalent to planting about 64 million trees. Moreover, replacing mercury vapor lamps has mitigated associated environmental pollution.\\n\\nIn terms of energy savings, the LED lamps reduce electricity consumption by about 185 million kWh annually.This greatly lowers the overall power demand from street lighting and helps reduce the load and generation costs for power suppliers.\\nNew Taipei City spans a wide area with over 256,000 streetlights in total. In the first phase (October 2020 to April 2021), the City prioritized replacing about 42,000 early-installed LED lamps that had reached high failure rates after being subsidized by the Bureau of Energy in 2013. In the second phase (October 2023 to October 2024), the remaining 214,000 aging LED streetlights were replaced. This comprehensive replacement not only reduced electricity expenditures but also significantly improved lighting quality, receiving positive feedback from the public.\\n\\nLink: \\n1.New Taipei City's Streetlight Replacement Project: Illuminating a Brighter Future\\nhttps://wedid.ntpc.gov.tw/Governance/Detail/0YVPOegylWb6\\n\\n2.Energy-saving Street Lamps Illuminate the Road to March Toward a Low-carbon City in New Taipei City \\nhttps://www.cw.com.tw/article/5119866",
