        "question_text": "Use this field to provide any additional information or context that you feel is relevant to your jurisdiction's response. Please note that this field is optional and is not scored/assessed.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "Further information": "According to Article 3 of Taiwan's Electricity Act, the analysis, formulation, and promotion of electricity policies fall under the jurisdiction of the central government. Taiwan's electricity supply is planned and managed by the Taiwan Power Company (Taipower), a state-owned enterprise authorized by the central government. Taipower operates power plants across the country and distributes electricity to all cities and counties in a unified manner.\\n\\nAs such, responses to questions 4.1, 7.1, and 9.2 of this questionnaire—regarding electricity mix restructuring, renewable energy targets, and implementation progress—must be based on the central government's energy transition schedule. Likewise, the medium- and long-term reduction targets in question 6 must align with national energy transition plans. According to the current national roadmap, the emission factor of electricity is set to decrease to 0.424 kg CO₂e/kWh by 2025, and further to 0.319 kg CO₂e/kWh by 2030 (compared to 0.559 kg CO₂e/kWh in 2005). By 2050, the renewable energy share in the national electricity mix is expected to reach 60% to 70%.\\n\\nNew Taipei City continues to actively collaborate with the central government in promoting decentralized renewable energy installations, including geothermal power development, solar photovoltaic deployment, and biogas power generation. The city government has also identified potential public and private sites to facilitate citizen participation through subsidies and regulatory mechanisms. However, because electricity in Taiwan is centrally distributed, the outcomes of these local policies are reflected nationally, rather than solely in New Taipei City's GHG inventory. In addition, energy poverty and energy accessibility fall under the scope of national social protection policies. The central government regulates electricity pricing nationwide and has established an Electricity Price Stabilization Fund in accordance with Article 9 of the Electricity Act."
