        "Other types of governments engaged in the development, implementation and/or monitoring of component": "National-level government|State/Regional-level government",
        "Outline the purpose of this engagement": "The development of this component is required by the national government (e.g., by law, regulation and/or agreement)",
        "Comment": "On October 12, 2023, Taiwan promulgated the \\'Regulations on the Administration of Voluntary Greenhouse Gas Reduction Programs.\\' On August 29, 2024, three sub-laws were enacted regarding the carbon fee collection system: the \\'Carbon Fee Collection Regulations,\\' the \\'Voluntary Reduction Plan Management Regulations,\\' and the \\'Greenhouse Gas Reduction Targets for Carbon Fee Subjects,\\' officially marking the country's entry into the era of carbon pricing. Furthermore, according to Article 26 of the Climate Change Response Act, voluntary reduction credits can be used to offset greenhouse gas emissions, reduce carbon fee payments, and reduce the difference in carbon emissions from imported products. This provides a legal basis for achieving the 2050 net-zero emissions target and other carbon reduction policies. The government provides assistance and guidance to businesses to understand the relevant policies. Currently, there are 47 regulated businesses in Taipei, 45 of which are subject to carbon fees. To mitigate the impact of the carbon fee system on local businesses, in addition to continuing to provide voluntary reduction project guidance to help businesses develop carbon credits and enhance their carbon asset management capabilities, briefing sessions on voluntary reduction plans will be held starting in 2025 to assist businesses in securing preferential carbon fee rates, promote industry and policy alignment, and jointly advance toward net-zero emissions goals in line with international standards.\\n\\nAs of August 26, 2025, the Ministry of Environment has reviewed the voluntary reduction plans of nine businesses within Taichung City.\\n"
