        "Sectors most exposed^": "Water supply|Human health and social work activities|Other: everyone may have a risk of food poisoning|Manufacturing|Agriculture",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "\\tHigh temperatures are more likely to affect high-risk groups (such as the elderly, infants and young children, those with chronic illnesses, obese individuals, those taking medication, and those working outdoors), leading to heatstroke and other heat-related health problems, such as cardiovascular disease and respiratory issues.\\n\\tIn response to Taiwan's climate risks, during the hot season, the city government prioritizes the safety and health of homeless people by providing them with cooling supplies and showers. Since most homeless people are self-sufficient, the city government also actively promotes awareness of environmental risks among them, enabling them to adapt to high temperatures early. In recent years, there have been no fatalities among homeless people due to high temperatures, demonstrating the effectiveness of these measures.\\n\\tEstablishing a temporary shelter system to strengthen disaster response capabilities: The Taichung City Government has established a comprehensive temporary shelter system that can immediately, safely, and rapidly accommodate disaster victims, ensuring they are safe and free from fear as quickly as possible. \\n\\tConsolidate information on high-risk elderly individuals to improve emergency response efficiency: Regularly update and compile a list of elderly individuals living alone. In addition to regular care visits, this list also provides the Fire Department and other agencies with information on the living conditions of elderly individuals living alone in the area when needed, thereby enhancing the safety of these individuals.\\n\\tPotential hazards of hot weather: Due to climate change, hotter and more humid weather increases the risk of bacterial growth, making food storage more difficult and increasing the risk of food contamination. Food businesses must pay more attention to production processes, transportation, storage conditions, and personnel hygiene to avoid increasing the risk of food contamination and hazards. Consumers should enhance their food safety awareness, choose reputable stores, and ensure food is stored at the correct temperature to reduce the risk of food poisoning.\\n",
