        "Sectors most exposed^": "Agriculture",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Major climate disasters in the prefecture include low temperatures from January to March, droughts from January to February and September to October, summer typhoons, and high temperatures, resulting in farmers requiring assistance from local governments. A brief description is provided below:\\n1. Low temperatures are common from December of the previous year to March of the current year. Climate change affects the intensity and frequency of these low temperatures, causing frostbite or growth stagnation in crops such as high-grafted pears, necessitating regrafting.\\n2. Droughts are common from January to February and September to October. Global warming affects rainfall patterns, resulting in uneven rainfall and sudden downpours. This leads to reduced quality and yield of pears, apples, and corn due to water shortages.\\n3. Typhoons from July to October each year can cause flooding and high-speed wind damage in fields, reducing yields of crops such as soybeans, taro, watermelon, and bitter melon. Furthermore, typhoons overlap with the peach season, causing nearly ripe peaches and pears to fall to the ground, damaging the harvest. High humidity after typhoons can also cause pests and diseases.\\n4. Global warming is causing prolonged and elevated high temperatures across the country. High temperatures in September and October in this city can cause poor flower bud differentiation in loquats, potentially impacting yields the following year.\\n",
