        "Sectors most exposed^": "Human health and social work activities|Public administration and defence; compulsory social security|Forestry|Water supply|Accommodation and food service activities|Wholesale and retail trade; repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles|Fishing|Transportation and storage|Construction|Manufacturing|Agriculture|Education",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "1. Typhoons carry a large amount of rainfall and come with strong winds, which have a greater impact on people in flood-prone areas of Taichung City, such as the Da'an River, Dajia River, Wu River, and other river areas, especially indigenous people, low-income families, and marginalized/minority groups. For ordinary citizens, strong winds cause damage such as the collapse of roadside trees and scaffolding, road interruptions, and house flooding, as well as property damage and risks to life.\\n2. Heavy rainfall is accompanied by typhoon. Such violent storms will seriously affect crop production and harvest, and may cause collapse of roads and trees, river surges, bridge fractures, rock and soil collapses in mountain areas, etc., resulting in traffic interruption, and thus affecting the operation of transportation and public services.\\n3. During the flood season (May - November), heavy rainfall events and typhoons carrying frontal air currents result in inadequate drainage in the area, leading to flooding and obstruction of related roads, affecting the traffic. Surface runoff carrying soil and sand in the catchment area affects the water quality and turbidity of water storage facilities, resulting in the inability to supply water, indirectly affecting various water demand industries.\\n4. Typhoons from July to October each year can cause flooding and high-speed wind damage in fields, resulting in reduced yields of crops such as soybeans, taro, watermelon, and bitter gourd. In addition, the occurrence of typhoons overlaps with the peach harvest season, causing maturing peaches and pears to fall directly to the ground and damage the harvest. The high humidity after the typhoon can also cause plant diseases and insect pests.\\n",
