        "row_name": "Row 13",
        "Climate-related hazards^": "Extreme cold",
        "Vulnerable population groups most exposed": "Frontline workers|Marginalized/minority communities",
        "Sectors most exposed^": "Human health and social work activities|Accommodation and food service activities",
        "Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "\\tIn response to Taiwan's climate risks, Taichung City Government is concerned about the health and safety of homeless people during the cold winter months, providing them with warm clothing, hot meals, and temporary shelter. Since most homeless people are capable of self-care, the city government is actively promoting awareness of environmental risks and enabling them to adapt to colder temperatures. In recent years, there have been no fatalities among homeless people due to high temperatures, demonstrating the effectiveness of these measures.\\n\\tEstablishing a temporary shelter system to strengthen disaster response capabilities: The Taichung City Government has a comprehensive temporary shelter system that allows for immediate, safe, and rapid sheltering of disaster victims, ensuring they are safe and free from fear as quickly as possible.\\n\\tIntegrating information on high-risk elderly individuals to improve emergency response efficiency: A list of elderly people living alone is regularly updated and maintained. In addition to regular care visits, the list also provides the fire department and other agencies with information on the living conditions of elderly people living alone in the area when needed, enhancing their safety and protection. \\n\\tFrom December of the previous year to March of the current year, cold snaps are prone to occur, and climate change affects the intensity and frequency of cold snaps. Crops such as loquats, grafted pears, and grapes suffer frostbite or growth stagnation, resulting in a decline in quality or yield.\\n",
