      {
        "question_text": "Does your jurisdiction have a strategy or standard for reducing emissions from the jurisdiction's procurement and purchase of goods and services?",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "Response": "Yes",
        "Provide an attachment to the strategy or standards addressing emissions from the jurisdiction's procurement": "上傳_8.4_關於綠生活_ok.pdf",
        "Provide a link, if applicable, and highlight any specific action(s) the jurisdiction is implementing to reduce emissions from its own consumption": "1. Strengthening Green Procurement in Government Agencies\\n\\nAll government agencies continue to implement green procurement policies, actively selecting products and services with environmentally friendly features such as environmental labels, carbon footprints, and energy savings. In 2024, the government achieved a green procurement achievement rate of 99.46%, earning it the designation of \\'Excellent High-Performing Agency\\' by the Ministry of Environment, demonstrating the government's strong execution.\\n\\n2. Promoting Green Procurement in the Private Sector\\n\\nTo maximize the effectiveness of green procurement policies, the Environmental Protection Bureau actively held information sessions in 2024 to encourage private businesses and community groups to embrace green procurement. Through continued promotion and outreach, the total green procurement value of private businesses in Taipei reached NT$6 billion in 2024, demonstrating the growing importance of environmental responsibility and sustainable development within the business community. By prioritizing products and services with environmentally friendly features such as environmental labels, carbon footprints, and energy savings, businesses not only promote low-carbon consumption patterns but also contribute to the green transformation of the industrial chain and carbon emissions reduction, laying a solid foundation for Taipei's goal of achieving net-zero carbon emissions.\\n\\n1. Strengthening Green Procurement in Government Agencies\\nAll government agencies continue to implement green procurement policies, actively selecting products and services with environmentally friendly features such as environmental labels, carbon footprints, and energy savings. In 2024, the government achieved a green procurement achievement rate of 99.46%, earning it the designation of \\'Excellent High-Performing Agency\\' by the Ministry of Environment, demonstrating the government's strong execution.\\n\\n2. Promoting Green Procurement in the Private Sector\\nTo maximize the effectiveness of green procurement policies, the Environmental Protection Bureau actively held information sessions in 2024 to encourage private businesses and community groups to embrace green procurement. Through continued promotion and outreach, the total green procurement value of private businesses in Taipei reached NT$6 billion in 2024, demonstrating the growing importance of environmental responsibility and sustainable development within the business community. By prioritizing products and services with environmentally friendly features such as environmental labels, carbon footprints, and energy savings, businesses not only promote low-carbon consumption patterns but also contribute to the green transformation of the industrial chain and carbon emissions reduction, laying a solid foundation for Taipei's goal of achieving net-zero carbon emissions.\\n\\n"
      }
