        "Climate component": "Climate risk and vulnerability assessment",
        "Other types of governments engaged in the development, implementation and/or monitoring of component": "State/Regional-level government",
        "Outline the purpose of this engagement": "To facilitate the integration of this component into assessments and policy developed across different levels of government",
        "Comment": "In accordance with the Greenhouse Gas Reduction and Management Act, Taiwan adopts a phased and hierarchical approach to greenhouse gas (GHG) mitigation and management:\\n1.Central Government: Formulates the National Climate Change Action Plan and GHG Reduction Promotion Projects, integrating national economic, energy, and environmental conditions to serve as the overarching policy framework.\\n2.Central Sectoral Authorities: Based on the national action plan, sector-specific authorities (e.g., energy, manufacturing, transportation, residential, commercial, and agriculture) prepare GHG emission control action plans. These plans include sectoral reduction targets, implementation schedules, and economic incentive measures.\\n3.Local Governments (e.g., Taipei City Government): Following central government guidance, local governments revise and implement their GHG Control Action Plans. These plans must be approved by the central government and are subject to review and updates every five years."
