        "question_text": "Report your jurisdiction's main adaptation goals.",
        "row_order": 7,
        "row_name": "Row 7",
        "Select a reference ID for the goal": "Adaptation goal 6",
        "Adaptation goal^": "Enhancing Urban Water Supply System Resilience\\n",
        "Climate hazards that goal addresses^": "Extreme heat",
        "Base year of goal (or year goal was established if no base year)^": 2018.0,
        "Target year of goal^": 2050.0,
        "Description of metric / indicator used to track goal and evidence of implementation": "Taipei City has implemented a series of targeted measures to strengthen the resilience, safety, and sustainability of its urban water supply system:\\n1.Water Conservation and Reuse of Wastewater\\nIn 2023, Taipei promoted water conservation and wastewater recycling, achieving 1,007 metric tons of reused water.\\n2.Water Supply Quality\\nThe tap water supply quality compliance rate reached 100% throughout 2023, ensuring safe and reliable access to drinking water for all residents.\\n3.Wastewater Treatment\\nAs of 2023, Taipei achieved a 100% wastewater treatment rate, demonstrating full coverage of wastewater management across the city.\\n4.Feitsui Raw Water Pipeline Project\\nThe Feitsui Raw Water Pipeline Project, which began in July 2019, is scheduled for completion in 2024. The project involves a 2.8-kilometer tunnel excavation, significantly enhancing the stability and redundancy of the city's raw water supply system.\\n5.Reducing Water Loss\\nSince 2006, Taipei Water Department has implemented a 20-year Water Supply Network Improvement and Management Plan. The goal is to reduce leakage rates to 10% by the end of 2025. By the end of 2022, leakage rates in the service area had already been reduced to 11.20%.",
        "Comment": "In parallel, Taipei City Government has advanced resilience-oriented frameworks that integrate disaster preparedness with water management, including:\\n•\\tDisaster Protection Enhancement Plan - Building resilient communities by selecting one village in each of Taipei's 12 districts to establish disaster-prevention strategies, conduct environmental assessments, form emergency organizations, and carry out evacuation drills.\\n•\\tPost-Disaster Recovery and Reconstruction Plan - Ensuring effective recovery through standard operating procedures, financial measures, livelihood arrangements, infrastructure restoration, industrial recovery, environmental rehabilitation, and psychosocial support for affected residents.\\n•\\tCommunity Flood Resilience Project - Led by the Hydraulic Engineering Office, focusing on non-structural measures to strengthen community flood preparedness. In 2021, three pilot districts were designated as demonstration communities, leveraging open data platforms for pre-disaster planning, real-time response, and post-event recovery.\\n"
