        "Target year of goal^": 2030.0,
        "Description of metric / indicator used to track goal and evidence of implementation": "1.Build a heatwave early warning system: Strengthen horizontal communication within Taipei City Government.\\n2.Develop a citywide disaster emergency notification system: Ensure coordinated response among all relevant bureaus and departments.\\n3.Heatwave reporting, feedback, and disaster assessment: Implement real-time monitoring, reporting, and evaluation of heatwave-related impacts.",
        "Comment": "Activation Standards and Response Procedures\\n1.Activation criteria: The system is triggered based on high-temperature alerts issued by the Central Weather Bureau (CWB), specifically Orange and Red Warnings.\\n2.Notification to city bureaus: Ten Taipei City Government bureaus are informed to implement high-temperature response measures, including:\\n•High-temperature water spraying\\n•Irrigation of public greenery and plants\\n•Emergency medical services, ambulance dispatch, and food industry guidance\\n•Inspection of outdoor laborers exposed to high temperatures\\n•Care for isolated residents (elderly, disabled) and homeless people\\n•Food safety awareness campaigns\\n•Prevention of heat-related injuries among students\\n•Riverbank inspections, preparation of debris removal capacity, and operation of flood control facilities\\n3.Reporting and consolidation: All bureaus report their execution status to the Environmental Protection Bureau for central consolidation.\\n________________________________________\\n2024 Heatwave Early Warning Performance (Year 113 of ROC Calendar)\\n•Total alerts issued: 33 warnings\\n•High-temperature water spraying: 2,247 km\\n•Plant irrigation area: 2,412,586 m²\\n•Emergency medical services provided: 4 people\\n•Emergency rescue interventions: 21 people\\n•Food industry guidance: 426 cases\\n•High-temperature labor inspections: 738 cases\\n•Care for isolated elderly and homeless: 13,166 people\\n•Food safety campaigns at markets and centralized vendor areas: 2,384 cases\\n•Riverbank inspections: 11 times\\n•Preparedness for debris removal capacity: 22 sites\\n•Operation of flood interception facilities: 154 times"
