        "Target status and progress made towards target": "Underway - significant progress made",
        "Please explain": "Taipei City has committed to a science-based long-term target to achieve 100% GHG reduction by 2050 compared to 2005 levels, reaching net zero emissions. This target aligns with the IPCC 1.5°C pathway, the IEA Net Zero Roadmap, and global best practices, positioning the City ahead of national commitments. Under the BAU scenario, Taipei would emit 12.26 million tCO₂e by 2050, which highlights the urgent need for a comprehensive cross-sector transformation. Guided by scientific methodologies, the City has systematically assessed climate risks and impacts, and will drive the transition through robust governance frameworks and concrete actions.\\nThe City's net zero strategy is driven by three major pathways, complemented by enhanced carbon sinks and emerging zero/negative-carbon technologies:\\n1. Building Sector - Smart Zero-Carbon Buildings: By 2050, all new, commercial, and public buildings must meet Class 1+ energy efficiency standards, using at least 55% renewable or hydrogen energy, while general buildings must use at least 20%. Existing buildings will undergo mandatory energy audits and retrofits, with public buildings renovated at 3% of total floor area annually.\\n2. Transportation Sector - Green and Low-Carbon Mobility: By 2050, 80% of trips will be made via green transportation. Private vehicles will be 95% electrified, with large-scale adoption of hydrogen and commercial EV fleets. Shared mobility will expand to 27,500 vehicles, and the public bike system to 21,500 units with 596 km of lanes. Low-carbon zones will cover the entire city, restricting high-carbon vehicles.\\n3. Waste Sector - Total Recycling and Zero Waste: By 2050, the resource recovery rate will reach 80% and wastewater treatment coverage 98%. Incinerators will be transformed into green power plants, integrated with facilities for food waste, bottom ash, and resource recovery to form a circular energy park. Advanced CCUS technologies will be deployed to eliminate residual emissions.\\n\\nThis 2050 net zero target is designed as the culmination of the City's SBT-aligned trajectory—40% by 2030, 65% by 2040, and 100% by 2050—ensuring coherence with central government policies on renewable energy, hydrogen, and electric mobility, while keeping flexibility for technological innovation.\\n"
