        "row_order": 7,
        "row_name": "Row 7",
        "Area of plan, policy and/or strategy": "Health and wellbeing",
        "Name of plan and URL link, if applicable": "Taipei City Disaster Prevention and Relief Plan\\nhttps://eocen.gov.taipei/\\n",
        "Current status of plan": "In implementation",
        "Boundary of plan relative to jurisdiction boundary": "Same - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "Year of formal approval of plan": 2021.0,
        "End of year plan": 2030.0,
        "Comment": "In response to global climate governance, the City will follow international conventions to move toward the 2050 net zero greenhouse gas emissions target, to fulfill the obligations of global village citizens, and to share the international responsibility for carbon reduction, and on the basis of the 2030 United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (based on the principle of \\'from the inside to the outside, from public sector to private sector\\'), to propose a net zero strategic pathway blueprint, to complement the national energy and industrial transformation, and to continuously promote multiple climate actions, regularly review the carbon reduction targets, and gradually realize being a zero-carbon city.This plan seeks to establish a “livable and sustainable city” with “disaster resilience” by advocating and enhancing disaster risk governance and climate change adaptation. In addition to the characteristics of disasters experienced by Taipei City in past years, this plan also keeps up with the international trends for disaster mitigation. On the basis of 2015-2030 Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction (SFDRR) developed by “the third UN World Conference on Disaster Risk Reduction” in 2015, all the policies and results in Taipei City were reviewed. Anchored in the perspectives of a local government but aiming for global goals, two plan objectives and four strategic guidelines were mapped out to advocate disaster prevention awareness and capability across-the-board."
