        "Climate hazard(s) that action addresses": "Infectious disease",
        "Action description and web link to further information^^": "Dengue Fever and Vector-Borne Disease Prevention Measures - Taipei City\\n1. Integrated Interdepartmental Response\\nThrough the “Capital Living Circle Dengue/Chikungunya Prevention Plan,” Taipei City integrates cross-departmental communication and collaboration among the Department of Health, Environmental Protection, Civil Affairs, Education, and other relevant units during routine periods and upon confirmed local dengue cases. These measures aim to prevent secondary community outbreaks.\\n2. Expansion of NS1 Rapid Test Medical Facilities\\nThe City has expanded the number of NS1 rapid test medical facilities to 124 locations, including 25 hospitals and 99 primary care clinics. This ensures early detection, diagnosis, and treatment of dengue cases while mitigating the risk of epidemic expansion.\\n3. GIS-Based Vector Surveillance\\nUtilizing the Vector-Borne Disease Prevention Information Integration System (GIS), Taipei City monitors mosquito density indices in high-risk community locations (vacant houses, empty lots, markets, etc.). This system provides real-time epidemiological and geospatial data to enable precise, targeted vector control interventions.\\n4. Community-Based Epidemic Prevention Teams\\nTwelve district-level epidemic prevention teams have been recruited and trained to strengthen local vector control awareness in communities and schools. This initiative enhances community knowledge of dengue prevention and allows rapid mobilization during outbreaks, thereby reinforcing community epidemic prevention capacity.\\n\\nReference: Taipei City Department of Health - Dengue Fever Prevention Zone\\nhttps://health.gov.taipei/Content_List.aspx?n=8F74E2EF04E02EB6",
