    "q4_8": [
      {
        "question_text": "Report on how climate change impacts health outcomes and health services in your jurisdiction.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "Health area affected by climate change": "Health outcomes",
        "Identify the climate hazard(s) that most significantly impact the selected health area": "Heat stress|Extreme heat|Infectious disease|Hurricanes, cyclones, and/or typhoons|Coastal flooding (incl. sea level rise)|Extreme cold|Extreme wind|Urban flooding|Heavy precipitation",
        "Identify the health issues driven by the selected climate hazard(s)": "Water-borne infections and illnesses|Food-borne infections and illnesses|Disruption of health-related services|Exacerbation of non-communicable disease symptoms - respiratory disease|Cold-related illnesses|Vector-borne infections and illnesses",
        "Timeframe of impact": "Long-term (after 2050)",
        "Identify which vulnerable populations are affected by the selected health issue(s)": "Outdoor workers|Vulnerable health groups",
        "What factors affect your jurisdiction's ability to address the selected health issues": "Lack of political priority|No factors affect the jurisdiction's ability to address health issues|Lack of expertise/technical capacity",
        "Comment": "1.\\tWhite Paper on Policies Addressing the Health Impacts of Climate Change\\n2.\\tVector-borne diseases are driven by extreme weather events. Flooding often leaves behind stagnant water, and rising temperatures create breeding grounds for disease-carrying mosquitoes. Dengue fever is currently the most prevalent vector-borne disease in Taiwan. Addressing mosquito-borne diseases under extreme climate conditions requires tackling root causes—such as eliminating standing water and improving flood management—rather than attributing them solely to climate change.\\nRespiratory and foodborne infectious diseases linked to extreme climate conditions should be mitigated through strengthened public health education, promotion of hand hygiene, and other good personal habits. Thus, these cannot be classified purely as direct climate-related outcomes either."
      }
    ],
