    "q4_12": [
      {
        "question_text": "Report the total quantity of food that is procured (in tonnes) for government-owned and/or operated facilities (including municipal facilities, schools, hospitals, youth centers, shelters, public canteens, prisons etc.). If available, please provide a breakdown per food group.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "Total quantity of food procured (tonnes)": 14672.74,
        "Breakdown of procured food by food group": "Schools: 14,400 tonnes. Hospitals: 272.74 tonnes.",
        "Year data applies to": 2024.0,
        "Comment": "Safe Food Program (Department of Education) (To promote organic and safe cultivation and to advance sustainable local production and consumption (tycg.gov.tw)\\n1. Contents: To safeguard student health and provide nutritious, safe school lunches, and in compliance with amendments to the School Health Act prohibiting the use of genetically modified fresh foods and their primary processed products, Taoyuan City launched the “Safe Food” policy in 2015. Since 2016, schools have used only non-GMO ingredients daily, while serving organic vegetables three times per week and traceable agricultural products once per week. In 2024, a budget of NT$194.8 million (fully subsidized by the city government, with no added cost to parents) was allocated. This policy has stimulated the development of organic agriculture in Taoyuan while ensuring that nearly 210,000 students enjoy safe and locally sourced food.\\n2. Relevant agencies—the Department of Education, Department of Agriculture, and Department of Public Health—have jointly formed the Safe Food Joint Inspection Task Force. The task force enforces end-to-end inspection and control across farms, supply platforms, and processing plants. Farm shipment records are subject to audit when necessary, and substitute farms used to address temporary supply shortages must also be certified organic to ensure students receive the healthiest, highest-quality food."
      }
    ],
