      {
        "question_text": "Does your jurisdiction have a strategy or standard for reducing emissions from the jurisdiction's procurement and purchase of goods and services?",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "Response": "Yes",
        "Provide an attachment to the strategy or standards addressing emissions from the jurisdiction's procurement": "Taoyuan City Green Procurement Program 2024.xlsx",
        "Provide a link, if applicable, and highlight any specific action(s) the jurisdiction is implementing to reduce emissions from its own consumption": "In line with the Ministry of Environment's Green Procurement Program for Private Enterprises and Organizations, Taoyuan City has promoted green procurement since 2016, incorporating local self-government regulations. All government agencies, schools, and enterprises above a designated scale are required to implement green procurement practices, supporting the city's net-zero and sustainable living policies by prioritizing low-carbon, sustainable products. The defined categories of enterprises include:\\n1. Enterprises: Companies, businesses, private factories, mines, salt works, farms, ranches, forestry operations, tea farms, media, cultural, public welfare, and cooperative enterprises located in the city with more than 500 employees.\\n2. Tourism hotels: Tourist hotels located within the city.\\n3. Hotels: Hotel operators within the city with more than 80 guest rooms.\\n4. Hospitals: Hospitals located in the city.\\nTo encourage enterprises to continue implementing green procurement and to reinforce their role as pioneers in sustainability, the Department of Environmental Protection, Taoyuan City Government annually commends those reporting green procurement expenditures exceeding NT$5 million in the previous year. Starting in 2025, additional recognition will be awarded to companies that have continuously reported green procurement for ten consecutive years. These measures aim to safeguard global sustainability and reinforce corporate social responsibility."
      }
